<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="0" pageNumber="98" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1905,2031]" pageId="0" pageNumber="98">“In the genus group, two or more available names established with the same spelling are homonyms” [Code, Article 53.2], and “A junior homonym … must be rejected and replaced either by an available and potentially valid synonym … or, for lack of such a name, by a new substitute name … with its own author and date” [Code, Articles 60.1, 60.3].</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,152,868]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
Surprisingly, trypanosome researchers have failed to notice that: 1) the subgeneric name 
<taxonomicName authority="Anez, 1982" authorityName="Anez" authorityYear="1982" box="[1103,1321,152,175]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Tejeraia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1103,1191,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Tejeraia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1198,1321,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref1691" refString="Anez, N. (1982) StUdies on Trypanosoma rangeli Tejera, 1920. IV-A reconsideration of its systematic position. Memorias do Instituto Oswaldo Cruz, 77, 405 - 415. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0074 - 02761982000400007" type="journal article">Añez, 1982</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is a junior homonym of the generic name 
<taxonomicName authority="Diaz-Ungria, 1963" authorityName="Diaz-Ungria" authorityYear="1963" box="[486,785,186,209]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Tejeraia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[486,571,186,209]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Tejeraia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[581,785,186,209]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref1738" refString="Diaz-Ungria, C. (1963) Nematodes parasites, noUveaUx oU interessants, dU VenezUela. Annales de Parasitologie, 38, 893 - 914. https: // doi. org / 10.1051 / parasite / 1963386893" type="journal article">Díaz-Ungría, 1963</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, in use for 
<taxonomicName authority="(Molin, 1860)" authorityName="Molin" authorityYear="1860" baseAuthorityName="Molin" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[905,1302,186,209]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Tejeraia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="mediospiralis">
<emphasis box="[905,1145,186,209]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Tejeraia mediospiralis</emphasis>
(Molin, 1860)
</taxonomicName>
(Nematoda: Secernentea: 
<taxonomicName box="[298,401,221,244]" class="Chromadorea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirurida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Nematoda" rank="order">Spirurida</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chitwood &amp; Wehr" authorityYear="1932" box="[415,566,221,244]" class="Chromadorea" family="Spirocercidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirurida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Nematoda" rank="family">Spirocercidae</taxonomicName>
), a parasitic roundworm infecting the stomach wall of the neotropical rodent, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Linnaeus, 1776)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1776" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[151,511,256,279]" class="Mammalia" family="Cuniculidae" genus="Cuniculus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="paca">
<emphasis box="[151,319,256,279]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Cuniculus paca</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1776)
</taxonomicName>
(Mammalia: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" authorityYear="1821" box="[658,759,256,279]" class="Mammalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Rodentia</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller &amp; Gidley" authorityYear="1918" box="[770,900,256,279]" class="Mammalia" family="Cuniculidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Cuniculidae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation box="[923,1122,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref1738" refString="Diaz-Ungria, C. (1963) Nematodes parasites, noUveaUx oU interessants, dU VenezUela. Annales de Parasitologie, 38, 893 - 914. https: // doi. org / 10.1051 / parasite / 1963386893" type="journal article">Díaz-Ungría 1963</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[1135,1278,256,279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2700" refString="Smales, L. R. (2004) Spirosprattus scyphiformis n. g., n. sp. (Nematoda: SpirUrida), from the Cape York Rat, Rattus leucopus (Gray, 1867) (Rodentia: MUridae), in Cape York, AUstralia. Comparative Parasitology, 71, 184 - 189. https: // doi. org / 10.1654 / 4108" type="journal article">Smales 2004</bibRefCitation>
); and 2) based on the provisions of the Code (Articles 53.2, 60.1, 60.3), 
<taxonomicName authority="Ozdikmen, 2009" authorityName="Ozdikmen" authorityYear="2009" box="[782,1036,290,313]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Aneza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[782,847,290,313]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Aneza</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[857,1036,290,313]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2670" refString="Ozdikmen, H. (2009) SUbstitUte names for some UnicellUlar animal taxa (Protozoa). Munis Entomology &amp; Zoology Journal, 4, 233 - 256." type="journal article">Özdikmen, 2009</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is the mandatory substitute name of 
<taxonomicName authority="Anez, 1982" authorityName="Anez" authorityYear="1982" box="[151,372,325,348]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Tejeraia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,239,325,348]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Tejeraia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[245,372,325,348]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref1691" refString="Anez, N. (1982) StUdies on Trypanosoma rangeli Tejera, 1920. IV-A reconsideration of its systematic position. Memorias do Instituto Oswaldo Cruz, 77, 405 - 415. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0074 - 02761982000400007" type="journal article">Añez, 1982</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,152,868]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
“If there is in the original publication itself … clear evidence of an inadvertent error, such as a lapsus calami or a copyist’s or printer’s error, it must be corrected” [Code, Article 32.5.1]. The genus-group name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ozdikmen" authorityYear="2009" box="[1211,1276,394,417]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Aneza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1211,1276,394,417]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Aneza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a patronym “dedicated to N. Anez who is the author of the preexisting subgenus 
<taxonomicName authority="Ozdikmen 2009" authorityName="Anez" authorityYear="1982" box="[895,980,429,452]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Tejeraia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[895,980,429,452]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Tejeraia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (
<bibRefCitation box="[1009,1188,429,452]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2670" refString="Ozdikmen, H. (2009) SUbstitUte names for some UnicellUlar animal taxa (Protozoa). Munis Entomology &amp; Zoology Journal, 4, 233 - 256." type="journal article">Özdikmen 2009</bibRefCitation>
). It was constructed by adding the suffix -a instead of the usual -ia to Anez (= Añez). The original publication (
<bibRefCitation box="[1150,1328,464,487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2670" refString="Ozdikmen, H. (2009) SUbstitUte names for some UnicellUlar animal taxa (Protozoa). Munis Entomology &amp; Zoology Journal, 4, 233 - 256." type="journal article">Özdikmen 2009</bibRefCitation>
) contains numerous mistakes and inconsistencies (e.g., “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiles &amp; Hassall" authorityYear="1925" box="[660,800,498,521]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Tripanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[660,800,498,521]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Tripanosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” instead of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gruby" authorityYear="1843" box="[938,1083,498,521]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[938,1083,498,521]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Trypanosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, “N. Anez” instead of N. Añez, referring to Protozoa as “animals”, use of the suffix -ia for other substitute names), which represent a latent temptation for subsequent authors to emend [Code, Article 33.2] 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ozdikmen" authorityYear="2009" box="[725,790,568,591]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Aneza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[725,790,568,591]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Aneza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by replacing -a with -ia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,152,868]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
The spiny subject of emendation of scientific names [Code, Article 33.2.3], which in countless cases has resulted in unjustified changes, has been lucidly discussed elsewhere (
<bibRefCitation box="[795,998,637,660]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2631" refString="Moore, R. C., Weller, J. M. &amp; Knight, J. B. (1942) ErroneoUs emendation of generic names. Journal of Paleontology, 16, 250 - 261." type="journal article">
Moore 
<emphasis box="[877,933,637,660]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">et al.</emphasis>
1942
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[1011,1155,637,660]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref1777" refString="DUbois, A. (2007) Genitives of species and sUbspecies nomina derived from personal names shoUld not be emended. Zootaxa, 1550, 49 - 68." type="journal article">Dubois 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Two conclusions can be reached. First, any word (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ozdikmen" authorityYear="2009" box="[488,553,672,695]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Aneza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[488,553,672,695]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Aneza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) may be used for a genus-group name provided that: a) it contains two or more letters, the first one in upper-case, all of them taken from the Roman alphabet; b) it is printed in a type-face font (normally italics) different from that of the text; and c) it is treated as a Latin noun in the nominative singular [Code, Appendix B6, Articles 11.2, 11.8]. Second, an ‛inadvertent error’ [Code, Article 32.5.1] must be of such nature that it is equally evident to all readers, which certainly is not the case of Özdikmen’s (2009) work. Hence, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ozdikmen" authorityYear="2009" box="[1256,1321,810,833]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Aneza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1256,1321,810,833]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Aneza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a valid genus-group name that shall not be emended.
</paragraph>
<subSection pageId="1" pageNumber="99" type="multiple">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,949,1735]" box="[151,1008,949,975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,1008,949,975]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,1008,949,975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
Should the name combination 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[532,892,949,975]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli" subGenus="Aneza">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[532,697,949,975]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Trypanosoma</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[714,789,949,975]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Aneza</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[806,892,949,975]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
be used?
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,949,1735]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
Because from the nomenclatural perspective 
<taxonomicName authority="Tejera, 1920" authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[635,1048,984,1007]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli" subGenus="Herpetosoma">
<emphasis box="[635,653,984,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[670,813,984,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Herpetosoma</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[830,907,984,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">rangeli</emphasis>
Tejera, 1920
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Tejera, 1920" authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[1101,1436,984,1007]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli" subGenus="Aneza">
<emphasis box="[1101,1120,984,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1137,1202,984,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Aneza</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1218,1295,984,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">rangeli</emphasis>
Tejera, 1920
</taxonomicName>
are available name combinations, the decision on which one to use does not depend on the Code, but on evolutionary and taxonomic considerations. Phylogenetic studies based on genetic markers (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation box="[1071,1300,1053,1076]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2844" refString="Stevens, J. R., Teixeira, M. M. G., Bingle, L. E. H. &amp; Gibson, W. C. (1999) The taxonomic position and evolUtionary relationships of Trypanosoma rangeli. International Journal for Parasitology, 29, 749 - 757. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0020 - 7519 (99) 00016 - 8" type="journal article">
Stevens 
<emphasis box="[1168,1230,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">et al.</emphasis>
1999
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2150" refString="HUghes, A. L. &amp; Piontkivska, H. (2003) Phylogeny of Trypanosomatidae and Bodonidae (Kinetoplastida) based on 18 S rRNA: evidence for paraphyly of Trypanosoma and six other genera. Molecular Biology and Evolution, 20, 644 - 652. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / molbev / msg 062" type="journal article">Hughes &amp; Piontkivska 2003</bibRefCitation>
; Maia da 
<bibRefCitation box="[452,637,1088,1111]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2454" refString="Maia da Silva, F., Noyes, H., Campaner, M., JUnqUeira, A. C. V., CoUra, J. R., Anez, N., Shaw, J. J., Stevens, J. R. &amp; Teixeira, M. M. (2004) Phylogeny, taxonomy and groUping of Trypanosoma rangeli isolates from man, triatomines and sylvatic mammals from widespread geographical origin based on SSU and ITS ribosomal seqUences. Parasitology, 129, 549 - 561. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0031182004005931" type="journal article">
Silva 
<emphasis box="[516,571,1088,1111]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[649,837,1088,1111]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref1807" refString="Fraga, J., Fernandez-Calienes, A., Montalvo, A. M., Maes, I., Deborggraeve, S., Buscher, P., DUjardin, J. - C. &amp; Van der AUwera, G. (2016) Phylogenetic analysis of the Trypanosoma genUs based on the heat-shock protein 70 gene. Infection, Genetics and Evolution, 43, 165 - 172. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. meegid. 2016.05.016" type="journal article">
Fraga 
<emphasis box="[718,774,1088,1111]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
) have shown 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[990,1096,1088,1111]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis box="[990,1096,1088,1111]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and members of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[151,294,1122,1145]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Herpetosoma</emphasis>
Doflein, 1901, to be more closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chagas" authorityYear="1909" box="[790,872,1122,1145]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="cruzi">
<emphasis box="[790,872,1122,1145]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. cruzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to salivarian trypanosomes (i.e., the salivarian condition of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[300,410,1157,1180]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis box="[300,410,1157,1180]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most likely is independently evolved). These studies have also shown that 
<emphasis box="[1292,1435,1157,1180]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Herpetosoma</emphasis>
(subsuming 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[282,385,1192,1215]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis box="[282,385,1192,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is polyphyletic, with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[627,730,1192,1215]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis box="[627,730,1192,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being more closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chagas" authorityYear="1909" box="[1054,1133,1192,1215]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="cruzi">
<emphasis box="[1054,1133,1192,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. cruzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kent, 1880)" authorityName="Kent" authorityYear="1880" baseAuthorityName="Kent" baseAuthorityYear="1880" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="lewisi">
<emphasis box="[1221,1435,1192,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Trypanosoma lewisi</emphasis>
(Kent, 1880)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,949,1735]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
The 
<typeStatus box="[246,292,1261,1284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">type</typeStatus>
species of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[554,697,1261,1284]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Herpetosoma</emphasis>
is precisely 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kent" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[830,916,1261,1284]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="lewisi">
<emphasis box="[830,916,1261,1284]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. lewisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, an obligatory endoparasite of rodents (though it sometimes infects humans) transmitted by rat fleas (
<bibRefCitation box="[731,904,1296,1319]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2242" refString="Lin, R. H., Lai, D. H., Zheng, L. L., WU, J ,, LUkes, J., Hide, G. &amp; LUn, Z. R. (2015) Analysis of the mitochondrial maxicircle of Trypanosoma lewisi, a neglected hUman pathogen. Parasites &amp; Vectors, 8, 665. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 13071 - 015 - 1281 - 8" type="journal article">
Lin 
<emphasis box="[780,837,1296,1319]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). The polyphyly of 
<emphasis box="[1128,1272,1296,1319]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Herpetosoma</emphasis>
(subsuming 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) motivated 
<bibRefCitation box="[355,568,1330,1353]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2844" refString="Stevens, J. R., Teixeira, M. M. G., Bingle, L. E. H. &amp; Gibson, W. C. (1999) The taxonomic position and evolUtionary relationships of Trypanosoma rangeli. International Journal for Parasitology, 29, 749 - 757. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0020 - 7519 (99) 00016 - 8" type="journal article">
Stevens 
<emphasis box="[444,497,1330,1353]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">et al.</emphasis>
(1999
</bibRefCitation>
; see also 
<bibRefCitation box="[668,849,1330,1353]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref1807" refString="Fraga, J., Fernandez-Calienes, A., Montalvo, A. M., Maes, I., Deborggraeve, S., Buscher, P., DUjardin, J. - C. &amp; Van der AUwera, G. (2016) Phylogenetic analysis of the Trypanosoma genUs based on the heat-shock protein 70 gene. Infection, Genetics and Evolution, 43, 165 - 172. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. meegid. 2016.05.016" type="journal article">
Fraga 
<emphasis box="[735,788,1330,1353]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
) to propose the subgenus to be ‛discontinued’ owing to ‛lack of evolutionary and taxonomic relevance’. This conclusion appears to be based on the perception that all species originally assigned to a genus (or subgenus) are its inseparable members. In fact, the 
<typeStatus box="[1159,1205,1400,1423]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">type</typeStatus>
species is the only indispensable member of supraspecific taxa [Code, Article 61.1]. Other species can be and customarily are transferred among genera and subgenera based on evolutionary and taxonomic considerations, the most important of which is avoiding polyphyly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,949,1735]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
Based on current phylogenetic evidence, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[695,809,1538,1561]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis box="[695,809,1538,1561]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
must be excluded from the therefore monophyletic 
<emphasis box="[151,294,1573,1596]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Herpetosoma</emphasis>
. This subgenus (excluding 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[604,711,1573,1596]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis box="[604,711,1573,1596]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) designates a deep-rooted, thus evolutionarily and taxonomically relevant clade within the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gruby" authorityYear="1843" box="[497,642,1608,1631]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[497,642,1608,1631]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Trypanosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Regarding 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[776,881,1608,1631]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis box="[776,881,1608,1631]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, users of trypanosome taxonomy have two options for its subgenus: 
<taxonomicName authority="Tejera, 1920" authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[338,785,1642,1665]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli" subGenus="Schizotrypanum">
<emphasis box="[338,357,1642,1665]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[374,546,1642,1665]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Schizotrypanum</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[563,640,1642,1665]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">rangeli</emphasis>
Tejera, 1920
</taxonomicName>
, if the close phylogenetic relationship of the species with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chagas" authorityYear="1909" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="cruzi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T. cruzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
needs to be emphasized (see 
<bibRefCitation box="[553,818,1677,1700]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref2770" refString="Stevens, J. R. &amp; Brisse, S. (2004) Systematics of trypanosomes of medical and veterinary importance. In: MaUdlin, I., Holmes, P. H. &amp; Miles, M. A. (Eds.), The trypanosomiases. CABI PUblishing, Cambridge, MA, pp. 1 - 23. https: // doi. org / 10.1079 / 9780851994758.0001" type="book chapter">Stevens &amp; Brisse 2004</bibRefCitation>
); or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tejera" authorityYear="1920" box="[877,1081,1677,1700]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli" subGenus="Aneza">
<emphasis box="[877,896,1677,1700]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">T.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[917,982,1677,1700]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Aneza</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1004,1081,1677,1700]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">rangeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, if the species is judged to be sufficiently divergent from other neotropical trypanosomes (see 
<bibRefCitation box="[836,977,1712,1735]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" refId="ref1896" refString="Gibson, W. (2016) Kinetoplastea. In: Archibald, J. M., Simpson, A. G. B., Slamovits, C. H., MargUlis, L., Melkonian, M., Chapman, D. J. &amp; Corliss, J. O. (Eds.), Handbook of the Protists. Springer, Cham, pp. 1 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 3 - 319 - 32669 - 6 _ 7 - 1" type="book chapter">Gibson 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
